Rasuko 56 Monk--Tigerwalker 55 Ranger</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#2f2f4f><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub35.ezboard.com/bthesafehouse.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=sbikluclin>Sbik Luclin</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#FF0000>(4/18/02 1:56:52 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub35.ezboard.com/fthesafehouselaboratory.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2282.topic&index=8>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Are poisons neccessary?</span><hr size=1> Vindi was slowable by poisons, yes.  However, he's been tagged as immune to changes in attack speed now I think, so no slows of any sort will land on him.<br>
<br>
Basically, before the &quot;immune to slow&quot; tag was put in, a few high end mobs had crazy MR on them to keep people from slowing them.  You still *could* slow them with magic based slows if you loaded up the debuffs and got lucky I think, but in general it just wasn't worth trying.  That's where the rogues came in since most of those mobs didn't have unusually high PR, so you could land the rogue slow poison on them.  However, the rogue poisons generally tended to be fairly unreliable since they would wear off randomly.  Usually just a couple of ticks after application.<br>
<br>
As is stands, the only mobs that I'd consider landing slow poisons on are mobs that dispell and cure disease themselves.  Even then I'd be wary about it due to the aggro associated with using poisons.  Before all of the changes to Sontalak, I landed spine breaks on him just for giggles but like all of our slow poisons, they wore off randomly.  Sometimes they made a nice difference, sometimes they just gave me unneeded aggro that I had to get rid of.<br>
<br>
If any slow type spell lands on a mob (MR, PR, or DR based), then all types *can* land since that means the mob is not immune to slows.  They can't (currently) make it immune to DR slow, but not MR slow for example.  However, they can buff the various resists of the mob to such high levels, that for all practical purposes the mob is immune to MR, PR, and / or DR.  Of course, if you really want to you can try to land slows on mobs who aren't immune but just have super high MR since there is a small chance it'll work.  You'll just probably run all of your 'chanters and shamans oom, or more likely they'll just get summoned and eaten. <p><a href=http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=156429>Sbik Swashbucklugget</a><br>
